    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1366470354" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1366470354" />
    <a title="Melanti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3034846-melanti"><img alt="Melanti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1286146966p2/3034846.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1366470354?book_show_action=true">Aug 17, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melanti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melanti" href="/user/show/3034846-melanti">Melanti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/36146320-mermaid">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3034846-melanti?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3034846-melanti?shelf=e-book">e-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3034846-melanti?shelf=fairy-tales-folklore-and-mythology">fairy-tales-folklore-and-mythology</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1366470354" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11468495527825668844">The first half of this was a stronger book than the second half, IMO.<br/><br/>I was very pleased with how in-tune Turgeon was with HCA&apos;s Christian themes in the first half - and she managed to incorporate his themes without turning it into an explicitly Christian novel.<br/><br/>But somehow, once Lenia became human, her longing for a soul got lost amongst the love triangle. The love triangle is absolutely necessary for this book - don&apos;t misunderstand me - but in the first half it&apos;s clear she loves the idea of a so</span>
  <span id="freeText11468495527825668844" style="display:none">The first half of this was a stronger book than the second half, IMO.<br /><br />I was very pleased with how in-tune Turgeon was with HCA's Christian themes in the first half - and she managed to incorporate his themes without turning it into an explicitly Christian novel.<br /><br />But somehow, once Lenia became human, her longing for a soul got lost amongst the love triangle. The love triangle is absolutely necessary for this book - don't misunderstand me - but in the first half it's clear she loves the idea of a soul as much as she loves the idea of the prince. Or perhaps she loves the idea of a soul MORE than she loves the idea of the prince, because the whole reason she loves the idea of the prince is because she loves the fact that he has a soul. Yet, once she meets him in human form, it becomes a physical, rather than spiritual affair, and the soul is only mentioned as an afterthought a handful of times.<br /><br />The ending did surprise me a bit. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /><br />I'd read a review that mentioned that Turgeon had changed it to a happy(ier) ending. After the first half of the book, I'd thought that possibly Lenia would gain a soul by entering a convent - "marrying" God seemed to be a good work-around for the original ending without being trite.<br /><br />Unfortunately, Turgeon took the trite route of resolving the whole situation without anyone sacrificing anything life-altering. Yes, Lenia has to go back to the sea and leave her daughter behind. But she does not gain her soul and she does not die. Both, IMO, are important, fundamental aspects of the original story and this version seems lacking without them.<br /><br />And, it also bugs me a bit that HCA wouldn't have seen Turgeon's version as a happy ending since Lenia is left soul-less. After how consistently she follows HCA's themes in the first half, completely abandoning them for a simplistic ending was really disappointing. <br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11468495527825668844" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


